You squeeze the toothpaste
these guys get passed in 1

00:25:18.126 --> 00:25:18.778
second.
 

00:25:18.778 --> 00:25:23.750
If I want per square meter
we'll just call that 1.

00:25:23.750 --> 00:25:29.486
Therefore the intensity is
simply the energy density

00:25:29.486 --> 00:25:33.759
multiplied by the velocity of
light.

00:25:33.759 --> 00:25:39.358
That's the rate at which the
energy flows.

00:25:39.358 --> 00:25:43.371
So let us now calculate that
and you'll get a very

00:25:43.371 --> 00:25:45.088
interesting result.
 

00:25:45.088 --> 00:25:52.430
The intensity is equal to the
energy density times c.

00:25:52.430 --> 00:25:57.386
The energy density was
ε_0

00:25:57.386 --> 00:26:03.960
E_0^(2)
sin^(2)(ky - ωt).

00:26:03.960 --> 00:26:05.180
This is not the average energy.
 

00:26:05.180 --> 00:26:06.960
This is instantaneous.
 

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:09.368
I'll average it in a moment.
 

00:26:09.368 --> 00:26:15.820
Are you guys with me now
somewhere here,

00:26:15.820 --> 00:26:16.980
here?
 

00:26:16.980 --> 00:26:21.224
Now I'm going to write it as
follows, ε_0

00:26:21.224 --> 00:26:26.204
and E_0
then at B_0--I

00:26:26.204 --> 00:26:28.410
forgot a c here.
 

00:26:28.410 --> 00:26:29.250
You realize that?
 

00:26:29.250 --> 00:26:31.528
That's another c.
 

00:26:31.528 --> 00:26:35.904
Then E_0 is
B_0 times another c

00:26:35.904 --> 00:26:39.230
times sin^(2)(ky -
ωt).

00:26:39.230 --> 00:26:40.920
And what is that?
 

00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:43.067
c^(2)
ε_0 is

00:26:43.067 --> 00:26:44.318
1/μ_0.
 

00:26:44.318 --> 00:26:50.068
So E_0
B_0 over

00:26:50.068 --> 00:26:56.940
μ_0 sin^(2)(ky -
ωt).

00:26:56.940 --> 00:27:01.536
But if you now define a vector
S, it's called a

00:27:01.536 --> 00:27:06.513
Poynting vector,
which is spelled with a p,

00:27:06.513 --> 00:27:12.558
to be E x B over
μ_0.

00:27:12.558 --> 00:27:16.500
The magnitude of that vector is
precisely the intensity.

00:27:16.500 --> 00:27:20.422
The magnitude of S,
which you can either call

00:27:20.422 --> 00:27:24.730
S or you can call it
I, is exactly this.

00:27:24.730 --> 00:27:28.224
So E x B except
for a factor 1/μ_0

00:27:28.224 --> 00:27:31.721
not only gives you the direction
of the way of propagation it

00:27:31.721 --> 00:27:35.450
tells you how many watts are
going to cross a square meter,

00:27:35.450 --> 00:27:41.220
or how many joules are going to
cross square meter in 1 second.

00:27:41.220 --> 00:27:44.060
Now these are things you'll
find in all the textbooks,

00:27:44.060 --> 00:27:44.328
so.
 

00:27:44.328 --> 00:27:47.346
All I've done is take this u c,
put it in the formulas with

00:27:47.346 --> 00:27:50.519
E and bring B back
into the picture so that it's

00:27:50.519 --> 00:27:52.858
symmetric between E and
B,

00:27:52.858 --> 00:27:54.730
because this gives the
impression it's all electric.

00:27:54.730 --> 00:27:56.349
Remember, this is electric and
magnetic.

00:27:56.349 --> 00:27:57.910
They just happen to be equal.
 

00:27:57.910 --> 00:28:01.838
This way you can see the role
played by E and B.

00:28:01.838 --> 00:28:05.940
The Poynting vector tells you
the flux of energy.

00:28:05.940 --> 00:28:07.108
So here's one example.
 

00:28:07.108 --> 00:28:12.047
At the surface of the earth if
you take a square meter,

00:28:12.047 --> 00:28:15.430
and here's the sun,
emitting light.

00:28:15.430 --> 00:28:18.342
You can ask,
"What's the intensity of

00:28:18.342 --> 00:28:19.548
sunlight?"
 

00:28:19.548 --> 00:28:25.039
Anybody have an idea how many
watts per square meter from the

00:28:25.039 --> 00:28:25.589
sun.
 

00:28:25.589 --> 00:28:28.430
Student:  A thousand?
 

00:28:28.430 --> 00:28:30.690
Prof: Yes,
very close to a thousand.

00:28:30.690 --> 00:28:34.529
I think there's some other
numbers, but for our purposes

00:28:34.529 --> 00:28:38.088
it's very close to 1,000 watts
per meter squared.

00:28:38.088 --> 00:28:42.660
That's pretty amazing over the
entire surface of the earth

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:46.670
every second the sun is pumping
in 1,000 joules.

00:28:46.670 --> 00:28:49.430
And you've got to remember the
context of the sun.

00:28:49.430 --> 00:28:53.394
I mean, here is the sun and
here we are ninety-three million

00:28:53.394 --> 00:28:57.828
miles away, and the light energy
is going and this is our share.

00:28:57.828 --> 00:29:02.163
A tiny circle like 7,000 miles
in diameter you're intercepting

00:29:02.163 --> 00:29:05.999
the light, and every square
meter of it gets a thousand

00:29:05.999 --> 00:29:06.710
watts.
 

00:29:06.710 --> 00:29:08.997
You can see the stuff coming
out of the sun,

00:29:08.997 --> 00:29:10.858
its a prodigious amount of
light.

00:29:10.858 --> 00:29:13.618
Anyway, that's the electric
field.

00:29:13.618 --> 00:29:17.170
I mean, that's the intensity,
so let me write the following

00:29:17.170 --> 00:29:17.660
thing.
 

00:29:17.660 --> 00:29:21.230
This is oscillating rapidly
with time, so let's define an

00:29:21.230 --> 00:29:24.740
average intensity as the average
of the sine squared.

00:29:24.740 --> 00:29:26.981
That's E_0B
_0

00:29:26.981 --> 00:29:28.160
/2μ_0.
 

00:29:28.160 --> 00:29:31.957
All these averages are simply
half, anything involving in sine

00:29:31.957 --> 00:29:32.578
squared.
 

00:29:32.578 --> 00:29:34.140
I'm not going to worry about
the half,

00:29:34.140 --> 00:29:37.038
but if you took this to be the
average intensity you can ask,

00:29:37.038 --> 00:29:40.913
"How big is the electric
field that comes with it,"

00:29:40.913 --> 00:29:44.723
because that light is going to
be this electric and magnetic

00:29:44.723 --> 00:29:45.369
field.
 

00:29:45.369 --> 00:29:47.190
That's all light is.
 

00:29:47.190 --> 00:29:49.402
So the sunlight produces
electromagnetic field,

00:29:49.402 --> 00:29:52.480
is electromagnetic waves and
I'm asking, "How big is the

00:29:52.480 --> 00:29:53.779
E vector?"
 

00:29:53.779 --> 00:29:56.450
And all you have to do is stick
that into this number.

00:29:56.450 --> 00:29:59.226
If you want you can get rid of
B and go back to E

00:29:59.226 --> 00:30:01.509
because E is just
B times c.

00:30:01.509 --> 00:30:04.028
You'll find a pretty surprising
amount.

00:30:04.028 --> 00:30:07.880
It's roughly 1,000 volts per
meter.

00:30:07.880 --> 00:30:11.509
Remember electric field is
measured in volts per meter.

00:30:11.509 --> 00:30:14.778
What that means is if you took
the field,

00:30:14.778 --> 00:30:17.690
and it's uniform in space,
between one place and another

00:30:17.690 --> 00:30:20.598
place there's a potential
difference of 1,000 volts,

00:30:20.598 --> 00:30:23.886
or it'll take 1,000 joules to
shove a coulomb from lower

00:30:23.886 --> 00:30:25.798
potential to higher potential.
 

00:30:25.798 --> 00:30:29.794
That's a pretty strong field,
but it's very incoherent in

00:30:29.794 --> 00:30:30.650
direction.
 

00:30:30.650 --> 00:30:33.230
It's doing this for a while and
doing that for a while,

00:30:33.230 --> 00:30:36.230
but if you roughly approximate
it and just ask,

00:30:36.230 --> 00:30:41.277
"What is the average field
strength,"

00:30:41.277 --> 00:30:44.460
this is the number you get.
 

00:30:44.460 --> 00:30:49.107
So let's talk about one thing
which I've not discussed at all,

00:30:49.107 --> 00:30:53.223
which is, where are these
electromagnetic fields coming

00:30:53.223 --> 00:30:53.910
from?
 

00:30:53.910 --> 00:30:56.868
I said you don't need ρ,
you don't need I,

00:30:56.868 --> 00:31:00.354
you don't need the current,
you don't need the charge,

00:31:00.354 --> 00:31:02.588
these can exist in free space.
 

00:31:02.588 --> 00:31:04.849
But what's the origin of the
electromagnetic waves?

00:31:04.849 --> 00:31:05.980
Anybody know?
 

00:31:05.980 --> 00:31:07.990
When can you get them?
 

00:31:07.990 --> 00:31:10.039
It didn't happen in anything we
studied.

00:31:10.039 --> 00:31:10.838
Yes?
 

00:31:10.838 --> 00:31:12.848
Student:  Electron
changes energy level?

00:31:12.848 --> 00:31:14.836
Prof: Well,
you can say in the atom the

00:31:14.836 --> 00:31:17.441
electron changes energy level,
but before you do the quantum

00:31:17.441 --> 00:31:18.058
mechanics.
 

00:31:18.058 --> 00:31:22.058
In classical theory one can
ask, what is the electric field?

00:31:22.058 --> 00:31:26.598
When does the electric field
produce these waves?

00:31:26.598 --> 00:31:30.480
You take a static charge it has
a 1/r^(2) field which is

00:31:30.480 --> 00:31:31.920
pinned to the charge.
 

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:33.558
If you go too far from the
charge you don't see it,

00:31:33.558 --> 00:31:37.146
but these guys can go off into
space without being anywhere

00:31:37.146 --> 00:31:43.960
near a charge or current,
but what produces them?

00:31:43.960 --> 00:31:45.539
Yes?
 

00:31:45.539 --> 00:31:46.390
You don't know?
 

00:31:46.390 --> 00:31:46.970
Yep?
 

00:31:46.970 --> 00:31:48.380
Student:  When it
oscillates.

00:31:48.380 --> 00:31:48.848
Prof: Pardon me?
 

00:31:48.848 --> 00:31:49.690
Student:  When is
oscillates.

00:31:49.690 --> 00:31:51.000
Prof: Which oscillates?
 

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:52.519
Student:  The electric
field.

00:31:52.519 --> 00:31:55.276
Prof: The electric field
is itself oscillating,

00:31:55.276 --> 00:31:57.460
but what's producing the
electric field?

00:31:57.460 --> 00:32:00.829
What's the cause of the
electric field?

00:32:00.829 --> 00:32:01.839
Electric field fairy?
 

00:32:01.839 --> 00:32:02.430
Yes?
 

00:32:02.430 --> 00:32:04.410
Student:  When a charge
oscillates?

00:32:04.410 --> 00:32:06.528
Prof: Yes.
 

00:32:06.528 --> 00:32:09.644
In other words,
rather than oscillates the more

00:32:09.644 --> 00:32:13.029
general answer is whenever a
charge accelerates.

00:32:13.029 --> 00:32:16.348
This is a very important result.
 

00:32:16.348 --> 00:32:29.808
Waves are produced by
accelerating charges.

00:32:29.808 --> 00:32:32.714
If they travel at uniform
velocity like in a wire they

00:32:32.714 --> 00:32:35.510
don't produce oscillations,
electromagnetic waves,

00:32:35.510 --> 00:32:38.285
or if they're going in a
circuit at constant rate that

00:32:38.285 --> 00:32:39.279
doesn't produce.
 

00:32:39.279 --> 00:32:42.209
But if you have charges which
are say oscillating is one

00:32:42.209 --> 00:32:44.338
example when things are
accelerating,

00:32:44.338 --> 00:32:48.092
right, because you're going
back and forth when you radiate

00:32:48.092 --> 00:32:48.608
light.
 

00:32:48.608 --> 00:32:52.599
So every single source of
electromagnetic wave is

00:32:52.599 --> 00:32:54.430
oscillating charges.
 

00:32:54.430 --> 00:32:56.640
You can sort of imagine why
that will happen.

00:32:56.640 --> 00:32:59.380
I mean, if you took a capacitor
plate,

00:32:59.380 --> 00:33:01.460
and you connect it to an AC
source,

00:33:01.460 --> 00:33:04.785
let's say, there may be other
things to keep it from burning

00:33:04.785 --> 00:33:06.898
out,
then what will happen is

00:33:06.898 --> 00:33:11.126
charges will be like this for a
while then they've got to go

00:33:11.126 --> 00:33:14.710
back and forth in order to
change polarity with the

00:33:14.710 --> 00:33:18.199
alternating field,
therefore the charges are going

00:33:18.199 --> 00:33:20.422
back and forth,
and you have a time dependent

00:33:20.422 --> 00:33:21.328
electric field here.
 

00:33:21.328 --> 00:33:24.561
When you have a time dependent
electric field you'll have a

00:33:24.561 --> 00:33:27.905
magnetic field going around it
because the line integral of B

00:33:27.905 --> 00:33:30.858
will involve the rate of change
of electric flux.

00:33:30.858 --> 00:33:33.460
And that will also be time
dependent, but if that gets time

00:33:33.460 --> 00:33:35.746
dependent there'll be an
electric field going around

00:33:35.746 --> 00:33:36.150
that.
 

00:33:36.150 --> 00:33:39.193
So basically these will curl
around each other whenever

00:33:39.193 --> 00:33:42.073
they're dependent on time,
and they can then free

00:33:42.073 --> 00:33:44.900
themselves loose from the
capacitor and take off.

00:33:44.900 --> 00:33:47.874
All you need is two plates,
and an AC source,

00:33:47.874 --> 00:33:51.253
and you connect them,
you will make electromagnetic

00:33:51.253 --> 00:33:51.930
waves.
 

00:33:51.930 --> 00:33:53.921
You'll make them at the
frequency of the source,

00:33:53.921 --> 00:33:55.318
so you won't be able to see it.
 

00:33:55.318 --> 00:33:58.443
Your dog won't be able to see,
but some gadget will be able to

00:33:58.443 --> 00:33:59.108
pick it up.
 

00:33:59.108 --> 00:34:03.048
That's all you need,
oscillating charges.

00:34:03.048 --> 00:34:07.354
So what happens in a radio
station is you could imagine a

00:34:07.354 --> 00:34:10.659
simple radio station with an LC
circuit,

00:34:10.659 --> 00:34:12.389
the current is oscillating at
some rate,

00:34:12.389 --> 00:34:14.619
and part of the circuit is in
the antenna,

00:34:14.619 --> 00:34:17.498
and the charges are going up
and down as the current goes

00:34:17.498 --> 00:34:19.710
back and forth that sends out
the waves,

00:34:19.710 --> 00:34:20.760
and the waves come to your
house.

00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:22.119
So here's the picture.
 

00:34:22.119 --> 00:34:26.295
Here's the radio station,
and the waves are emitted in

00:34:26.295 --> 00:34:30.864
big circles, and this is your
house, and here's your little

00:34:30.864 --> 00:34:31.809
antenna.
 

00:34:31.809 --> 00:34:35.485
It's a piece of wire,
and the electric field,

00:34:35.485 --> 00:34:40.079
if it's polarized this way,
will move the charges up and

00:34:40.079 --> 00:34:44.340
down, and charges can be part of
an LC circuit.

00:34:44.340 --> 00:34:46.170
So here are the antennas,
if you like;

00:34:46.170 --> 00:34:47.360
part of the circuit.
 

00:34:47.360 --> 00:34:51.476
As the charge goes up and down
the AC current will try to flow

00:34:51.476 --> 00:34:51.949
here.
 

00:34:51.949 --> 00:34:55.322
And if you tune this capacitor
so that it resonates with the

00:34:55.322 --> 00:34:58.809
frequency you'll get a hefty
signal from the radio station.

00:34:58.809 --> 00:35:00.780
So in the end it's all charges.
 

00:35:00.780 --> 00:35:02.309
Charges produce the field.
 

00:35:02.309 --> 00:35:03.760
Charges respond to the field.
 

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:05.039
That was true in the static
case.

00:35:05.039 --> 00:35:07.010
That's true in the time
dependent case.

00:35:07.010 --> 00:35:08.000
Yes?
 

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:10.777
Student:  When you say
that the field if it's loose

00:35:10.777 --> 00:35:13.166
from the capacitor,
what do you mean free from the

00:35:13.166 --> 00:35:13.849
capacitor?
 

00:35:13.849 --> 00:35:17.295
Prof: It means it can go
thousands of miles from the

00:35:17.295 --> 00:35:18.010
capacitor.
 

00:35:18.010 --> 00:35:20.764
And if you simply look at the
Coulomb force due to the

00:35:20.764 --> 00:35:23.311
charges, the plus and minus
charges, they die like

00:35:23.311 --> 00:35:24.300
1/r^(2).
 

00:35:24.300 --> 00:35:27.360
So if you calculate
1/r^(2) you will get a

00:35:27.360 --> 00:35:31.059
negligible number compared to
the actual electric field.

00:35:31.059 --> 00:35:33.300
So it's really like you and
your parents.

00:35:33.300 --> 00:35:37.119
I mean, at some point you are
free from your parents.

00:35:37.119 --> 00:35:39.668
You are able to manage on your
own, but you had parents

00:35:39.668 --> 00:35:40.989
somewhere sometime,
right?

00:35:40.989 --> 00:35:41.820
That's what it is.
 

00:35:41.820 --> 00:35:44.090
The electromagnetic waves can
go on their own,

00:35:44.090 --> 00:35:46.159
but they are not produced on
their own.

00:35:46.159 --> 00:35:47.909
They're produced by charges.
 

00:35:47.909 --> 00:35:49.650
It is just that unlike the
static fields,

00:35:49.650 --> 00:35:52.800
which are very near the
currents and charges that

00:35:52.800 --> 00:35:55.762
produce them,
the time dependent fields

00:35:55.762 --> 00:35:57.599
propagate on their own.
 

00:35:57.599 --> 00:36:00.496
E keeps B alive
and B keeps E

00:36:00.496 --> 00:36:00.909
alive.
 

00:36:00.909 --> 00:36:02.210
If E tries to die
there's a

00:36:02.210 --> 00:36:04.340
dE/dT that
produces a B.

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:06.485
If the B tries to go
down it produces at

00:36:06.485 --> 00:36:08.909
dB/dT that
produces an E,

00:36:08.909 --> 00:36:10.309
so they go back and forth.
 

00:36:10.309 --> 00:36:12.706
It's really like oscillations
in which you have kinetic to

00:36:12.706 --> 00:36:13.590
potential transfer.
 

00:36:13.590 --> 00:36:15.940
You can have energy transfer.
 

00:36:15.940 --> 00:36:17.880
So the fields cannot die.
 

00:36:17.880 --> 00:36:21.226
They are self-sustaining,
but to get all of that physics

00:36:21.226 --> 00:36:24.389
you had to put the term that
Mr. Maxwell put in.

00:36:24.389 --> 00:36:27.190
Without that term you don't
have this phenomenon.

00:36:27.190 --> 00:36:29.340
You don't get it from statics.
 

00:36:29.340 --> 00:36:33.159
So one typical problem you have
is this radio station is,

00:36:33.159 --> 00:36:37.677
let's say, 100 kilowatts and
you're sitting here at some

00:36:37.677 --> 00:36:41.210
distance r from the radio
station.

00:36:41.210 --> 00:36:44.875
Then the intensity in your
house will be 100 kilowatts

00:36:44.875 --> 00:36:47.780
spread over a sphere of radius
R.

00:36:47.780 --> 00:36:51.650
That will be your intensity.
 

00:36:51.650 --> 00:36:54.052
Then you can go from the
intensity and translate it to an

00:36:54.052 --> 00:36:56.246
electric field and say,
"The electric field

00:36:56.246 --> 00:36:58.847
produced by the radio station
oscillates with the following

00:36:58.847 --> 00:36:59.429
amplitude.
 

00:36:59.429 --> 00:37:05.474
I've got to build a circuit
that's smart enough to pick up

00:37:05.474 --> 00:37:08.018
that tiny field."
 

